\subsection{Dataset Preparation and Experimental Setup}
To rigorously evaluate the Hybrid Ehrenfest Diffusion Acceleration (HEDA) framework, we utilized a range of datasets prepared to align with established experimental protocols. These datasets fell into two primary categories:

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Synthetic Benchmarks:} Artificially generated two-dimensional diffusion models were employed, providing controllable conditions for observing state propagation and convergence.
\item \textbf{Real-World Datasets:} Well-established datasets such as MNIST and CIFAR-10 were integrated into testing pipelines to demonstrate the method's effectiveness under practical scenarios.
\end{itemize}

Each dataset underwent standardized preprocessing involving normalization and splitting into training, validation, and testing sets without overlap. These measures ensured unbiased outcome evaluations.

For diffusion modeling tasks, both the proposed HEDA and the baseline ParaTAA methods were implemented using PyTorch. Hardware resources included NVIDIA Tesla T4 GPUs ensuring reproducible performance evaluation. Metrics assessed included fidelity scores (FID), inception scores, and convergence rates. Detailed configuration files and full code for replication are publicly accessible to promote open research practices.

